node.text:
“Families have all shapes and colors.”

CDR Hale Allegretti, the waterways management division chief at U. S. Coast Guard Sector San Francisco, speaks about the importance of being able to serve openly as #LGBTQ during his time in the military.

Allegretti, a #transgender service member, joined the U.S. Coast Guard under the Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell policy, which prohibited members from disclosing their orientation.

“Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell impacted me because I always felt like there was a wall of secrecy between me and my shipmates,” said Allegretti.

The Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell Repeal Act of 2010 ended the policy, thus allowing #LGBTQ people to serve openly in the United States Armed Forces.

“When you can put words to what you’re feeling and what you’re seeing and be supported by the people around you, to feel respected, to feel like you can serve in a safe place, there’s really no way to measure it,” said Allegretti. “It’s incredible.”

#PrideMonth #RepresentationMatters

Video by Petty Officer 2nd Class Brandon Giles U.S. Coast Guard Pacific Southwest

Nothing like conning a ship at 14 knots only 160 feet away from a fuel tanker, fill’er up!
•
Fueling at Sea (FAS) allows MUNRO to remain in the operational area without returning to port to refuel. FASing is more convenient and 8-10x faster than refueling with a fuel truck at a pier. 
•
Thank you to our @usnavy partners and the USNS John Lenthall (T-AO-189) for the assist!

This video highlights CGC MUNRO’s most recent Eastern Pacific counter drug patrol where the crew were protecting our national security in the midst of the pandemic. The Coast Guard and MUNRO continue to deter transnational organized criminals in pursuit of justice.  
•
MUNRO and attached Helicopter Interdiction Tactical Squadron (HITRON) were responsible for 20 boardings, 12 interdictions and seized a total of 16,265 lbs of cocaine and 11,650 lbs of marijuana with a combined wholesale value of $334 million.

node.text:
U.S. Coast Guard Cutter Campbell deploys to the Arctic in support of the search and rescue exercise SAREX ARGUS hosted by the Joint Arctic Command, alongside allies Denmark, France and the U.S. Navy. CGC Campbell assisted NOAA and the International Ice Patrol deploying 13 weather buoys and giving feedback on the ice state throughout Arctic waters. CGC Campbell and her crew earned the Arctic Service Medal for their deployment which was a historic first as this was the furthest north a medium endurance cutter has journeyed into the Atlantic Arctic. 

U.S. Coast Guard video by SN Kate Kilroy and CGC Campbell 
Music by ENS Middleton

node.text: Vessel Traffic Service Prince William Sound is a department of Marine Safety Unit Valdez, Alaska.  The VTS watch is housed in the Vessel Traffic Center, and is staffed 24 hours a day, 7 days a week by Coast Guard active duty and civilian personnel.  Our mission is to prevent accidents, loss of life, and damage to property and the environment.  Our primary function is to instill good order and predictability on the waters of the VTS Area by coordinating vessel movements through the collection, verification, organization, and dissemination of information. #USCG #USCGMSUValdez #marinesafety #valdez #valdezalaska #princewilliamsound

node.text: This weekend’s IG takeover is hosted by Marine Safety Unit Valdez, in beautiful Valdez, Alaska! Valdez is known for its snowy winters, 360 degree mountain views, great fishing (both commercial and recreational), and as the terminus of the Trans-Alaskan Pipeline. MSU Valdez is tasked with the safe navigation of vessels, preserving the waters and habitats, and enforcing protection of key critical infrastructure and commerce in Prince William Sound. The port of Valdez is also considered the northernmost ice free port in The United States. We are excited to share with you what we do here in rural Alaska over the course of the weekend! #USCG #USCGMSUValdez #marinesafety #valdez #valdezalaska #princewilliamsound

node.text: Other than servicing over 270 federal aids throughout the coast of FL, we also get to do some cool projects like this one we did a few weeks back. We got to deploy the SA WILLIAM FLORES statue in the ‘Circle of Heroes’ about 20 miles offshore of Tampa Bay.  William Flores was one of the heroes we had lost back in 1980 with the sinking of the USCGC BLACKTHORN. On January 28th 1980, while leaving Tampa Bay after the completion of the overhaul, she collided with the tanker SS Capricorn. Shortly after the collision, Blackthorn capsized, killing 23 of her crew. Each statue in the Circle of Heroes is in a specific location and facing East. ‘It will serve as an underwater monument and therapeutic dive site for veterans dealing with post-traumatic stress disorder, trauma and depression.’ Per the Tampa Bay Times

Station Portland covers search & rescue and law enforcement over one of the most visited attractions in Oregon, the Columbia River Gorge! 

From dozens of waterfalls to amazing views, this is where the majority of the crew spends time hiking and enjoying the outdoors! #PNW Videos taken by SN Mardock.
